    "side_effects_description": "The possible side effects of using Viguiera quinqueradiata improperly are gastrointestinal problems such as inducing nausea and vomiting due to its toxic compounds like sesquiterpenes and flavonoids, which can irritate the stomach lining and cause diarrhea. This can lead to dehydration and electrolyte imbalance if not properly managed. Moreover, Viguiera quinqueradiata can trigger allergic reactions in some individuals, including skin rashes, itching, and respiratory problems, such as coughing and difficulty breathing. These reactions are usually caused by an allergic response to the plant's allergenic compounds. In severe cases, improper use of Viguiera quinqueradiata can lead to anaphylaxis, a life-threatening allergic reaction.",
    "uses": "Viguiera quinqueradiata, commonly known as the \"Crown of the Andes,\" has been utilized in traditional medicine for its potential health benefits. The plant's extracts have been studied for their antioxidant, anti-inflammatory, and antimicrobial properties, which may contribute to its medicinal uses. Some research suggests that Viguiera quinqueradiata may possess hepatoprotective and nephroprotective effects, indicating its potential in protecting liver and kidney function. However, more comprehensive research is needed to confirm its efficacy and safety for human consumption. Further studies are required to fully understand the plant's medicinal properties and potential applications.",
    "taxonomy": "Viguiera quinqueradiata is a species of flowering plant in the sunflower family, Asteraceae. It is native to South America and belongs to the genus Viguiera. The genus Viguiera is classified under the tribe Heliantheae. Viguiera quinqueradiata is further classified as a member of the subfamily Asteroideae. This classification indicates its evolutionary relationships and place within the plant kingdom.",
    "benefits": "Viguiera quinqueradiata is also known as Goldeneye or Yellow Daisy. Research suggests that this plant may have various health benefits, including anti-inflammatory and antioxidant properties. Some studies indicate that extracts from Viguiera quinqueradiata may help protect against oxidative stress and cell damage. Additionally, the plant is said to have antimicrobial and antifungal properties, which could contribute to its potential health benefits. However, more research is needed to fully understand the therapeutic potential of Viguiera quinqueradiata.",
    "parts": "Viguiera quinqueradiata, also known as yellow marigold or Mexican tournesol, is a plant species native to Mexico and the southwestern United States. The medicinal parts of this plant are not well-documented, but it is known to have been used in traditional medicine by indigenous communities in Mexico. The roots and leaves of Viguiera quinqueradiata are thought to have been used to treat various ailments, including fever and inflammation. However, more research is needed to confirm the efficacy and safety of using these parts for medicinal purposes. Further studies on the plant's properties and potential uses are necessary to fully understand its medicinal value.",
    "intro": "Viguiera quinqueradiata, also known as \"tree marigold\", is a species of flowering plant in the sunflower family (Asteraceae). The tree marigold is valued for its potential health benefits, including anti-inflammatory and antimicrobial properties, which may aid in the treatment of various conditions such as wounds, infections, and respiratory issues. The bioactive constituents of Viguiera quinqueradiata include sesquiterpene lactones, flavonoids, and phenolic acids, which contribute to its medicinal properties. In traditional medicine, the tree marigold is often used to prepare herbal teas, infusions, and tinctures, as well as topical creams and ointments, to harness its therapeutic potential."
